{
  "doc_id": "28085",
  "text": "Some postulate that providing information about risks and complications causes undue and unnecessary anxiety, whereas others report that improving patient's knowledge about treatment reduces anxiety [CITATION_1] . Beresford et al. [CITATION_2] identified three groups of patients in terms of their information needs: (1) those requiring little or no risk information; (2) those requiring information about major risks; and (3) those requiring full risk disclosure. Because of this heterogeneity, patient preferences should be discussed before risk disclosure. Similarly, Bridson et al. [CITATION_3] advocate a more patient-centered method in which the clinician should ask patients their goals for treatment even before treatment options are discussed, in order to tailor the information to fit the context of the patient's objectives. Fraser [CITATION_4] suggests that doctors should neither insist on gaining fully informed consent from anxious patients nor deny detailed information to inquiring ones.",
